observations.recommendation:
We recommended the following:
a. That the Property Officer/Inventory Committee, in coordination with the Municipal Accountant, expedite the reconciliation of inventory reports with the accounting records, addressing the deficiencies noted in audit, and submit the final reconciled copies to the AT;
b. That the Municipal Engineer promptly provide the Municipal Accountant with the required COCs for all completed infrastructure projects to facilitate their transfer to the appropriate PPE accounts;
c. That the Municipal Accountant (i) conduct an immediate review and reclassify the 2,908 items recorded as PPE but valued below the ₱50,000.00 capitalization threshold, in compliance with COA Circular No. 2024-006; and (ii) prepare the necessary adjusting entries to transfer completed projects from the CIP account to the appropriate PPE accounts, and recognize the corresponding depreciation from the time the assets became available for use; and
d. That the Municipal Mayor, through the Municipal Accountant, Inventory Committee Head, and other concerned offices, (i) implement the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006; and (ii) initiate the disposal process of unserviceable properties in accordance with Section 79 of PD No. 1445.

We recommended that the:
Municipal Accountant and the Property Officer maintain complete and accurate property records such as PPELC and PC for all PPE with complete information and investigate the unreconciled difference of ₱14,694,742.50;
Municipal Mayor exert efforts to secure the land title for the untitled lot purchased by the municipality and take actual possession of the land.   It is his responsibility to ensure that all real estate properties are registered under the Torrens Title System and safeguarded from squatters and unlawful occupants;
Municipal Mayor, thru the Municipal Accountant, strictly comply with the documentary requirements to support the initial payment of land, to ensure that no inconveniencies  will be encountered in the titling of the land in favor of the Municipality and to ascertain whether the legality and valuation of this property was proper and reasonable; and
Property Officer immediately request the disposal of the unserviceable property to prevent their further deterioration and the Municipal Accountant disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the carrying amount of PPE retired from active use and held for disposal so as not to mislead users of the Financial Statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, thru the Municipal Accountant:
Send follow-up demand letters to the former elected officials and employees and those separated from the service by exerting effort in locating their present address and ensuring they receive the same to enforce immediate liquidation/settlement of  their cash advances;
Ensure strict compliance with the rules and regulations on  the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances as provided under COA Circular No. 97-002 and Section 89 of PD No. 1445 to prevent the grant of CAs without specific purpose and accumulation of outstanding balances;
Exert efforts to locate records and/or conduct inquiries pertaining to undetermined cash advances totaling ₱584,469.11 to enable reconciliation and/or adjustment in the books; and
Lastly, exhaust available remedies as provided under COA Circular No. 2012-004 to enforce full settlement/liquidation of all outstanding cash advances, otherwise institute appropriate administrative proceeding.

We recommended that the LCE instruct the Municipal Engineer and the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator to:
Ensure the optimum utilization of the 20% DF through prompt and efficient implementation of  all priority development projects within the budget year by proper planning to address the conditions/limitations that could hinder the timely implementation of projects;
Evaluate whether the programs and projects funded from previous years’ appropriations are still relevant and consider reprogramming them including the unexpended balances of the completed projects under 20% DF to other eligible projects development pursuant to Sectiion II. 5 of DILG Memorandum Circular No. 99-66 to maximize utilization of the fund;
Ensure that projects included in the 20% DF have a long term effect/benefit in the socio economic condition  of the constituents, considering the unique environment of the municipality and ensure that PPAs under the 20%DF are among those allowable development projects as enumerated in JMC No. 2017-01; and
Include only PPAs which are feasible and applicable to the conditions/limitations in  the implementation of  20% DF projects in the island municipality.

We recommended that the management, thru the Municipal Accountant, send Demand Letters to former elected officials and employees and those separated from the service to immediately liquidate/settle their cash advances;

The Municipal Accountant trace back the records of unidentified cash advances totaling ₱584,469.11 and seek the assistance of the former Municipal Accountant for proper identification and recording of the said long outstanding cash advances; and

Ensure strict compliance with the rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances as provided under COA Circular Nos. 97-002 and Section 89 of PD No. 1445 to prevent the accumulation of outstanding balances of cash advances.

We recommended that the management, thru the Municipal Accountant, send demand letters to the former elected officials and employees and to those already separated from the service to immediately liquidate/settle their cash advances totaling ₱5,806,105.00;
The Municipal Accountant trace back the records of unidentified cash advances totaling ₱584,469.11 and seek the assistance of the former Municipal Accountant for proper identification and recording of the said long outstanding cash advances; and
Ensure strict compliance with the rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances as provided under COA Circular No. 97-002 and Section 89 of PD No. 1445 to prevent the accumulation of outstanding balances of cash advances.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. direct the Municipal Budget Officer to strictly adhere with Section 15 of RA No. 9344 by allocating at least one per cent of its IRA for programs, projects and activities for the protection of children; and
b. advise the LCPC to prepare and submit immediately the following reports to the Office of the Auditor:
• Council’s Annual Work and Financial Plan;
• Local Development Plan for Children;
• Local Code for Children;
• Local State of Children’s Report;
• Local Investment Plan for Children; and
• Accomplishment Reports

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct:
	the Municipal Accountant to maintain PPELC for each category of property and WOABSLC for each type of livestock;
	the MGSO to maintain Property Cards to account for their receipt and disposition;
	the MGSO to send concerned staff of the Inventory Unit to training on Supply and Property Management;
	the Municipal Accountant and the MGSO to exert efforts to reconcile the accounting and property records;
	the Inventory Committee to complete the yearly physical inventory count of all property and to submit the reports thereon to concerned offices not later than January 31 of each year;
	the Municipal Accountant to provide depreciation expenses for all depreciable assets in accordance with Paragraph Nos. 66, 67, 69 and 71 of PPSAS 17; and
	the Municipal Accountant to draw a Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) to record the reconciliation.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct:

the Municipal Accountant to provide Subsidiary Ledgers for Furniture and Fixtures account with details on the acquisition, description, custody, estimated life, rate of depreciation, disposal and other information on the property;

the creation of a special group/task force to undertake the immediate reconciliation of the variance between the balance appearing in the Property Inventory Report and Accounting Records;


the Municipal Accountant to analyze the composition of the Office Equipment, Other Machineries and Equipment and Furniture and Fixtures Account and reclassify them to their proper PPE account;

the concerned official to explain why the P3,865,682.97 assets enumerated above shows no balance per stock card and why these were not recorded in the books, as prescribed under PPSAS No. 17; and

strict adherence to the applicable laws, rules and regulations on PPE to prevent the incurrence of the deficiencies noted.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Pay all disbursement in checks except in certain instances when it may be very difficult, impractical or impossible to make payments by checks;

Refrain from granting any elective official of cash advances except for official travel;


Duly designate a Special Disbursing Officer for special cash advances; and


Strictly implement all the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant to:

submit all the documents to establish the propriety, validity and regularity of transactions;


explain why the disbursements were not paid directly to the caterer/supplier but through reimbursement and cash advances;


explain how they were able to make canvass from suppliers from Metro Manila and at the same day executed a Purchase Order (PO) and paid the amount due;

Explain why IT equipment were not installed in the FITS Center and why the farm primers/books and other materials were not found complete; and

Explain why the farm primer entitled “mga kasagarang sakit ng saging”, “major diseases of onion”, “coco coir production technology”, “bamboo”, “off season tomato production”, “jatropha seedling production”, “artificial insemination in sheep”, “papayang uwak”, and “bulusan volcano matural park” were of different prices in the PO. 

Moreover, we recommended that the Municipality refrain from making cash advances and instead directly pay or issue the check in the name of the supplier.

We recommended that the Management:  

submit the perfected contract and its supporting documents within five working days from execution and ensure compliance with COA Circular Nos. 76-34 and 87-278 as restated under COA Circular No. 2009-001 dated February 12, 2009; 

post in the PhilGEPS website the Notice to Proceed (NTP) in accordance with Section 37.4.2 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;


comply with the prescribed period of action on procurement activities in Annex “C” and other applicable provisions of the revised IRR of RA No. 9184;

submit the certifications, authority and other documents in compliance to Section 7, EO 109 and the revised IRR of RA No. 9184; 

explain why retention money equivalent to 10% was not deducted in each progress payment; and 


explain why the project was completed beyond the stipulated contract period and require the contractor to submit the Notice of Work Suspension and Certification (Weather Chart) from PAGASA Weather Station otherwise, impose liquidated damages for incurring delay.
